Plot.
This Disney feature-length cartoon combines the most entertaining elements 
of Lewis Carroll's Alice in Wonderland and Through the Looking Glass. Chasing 
after the White Rabbit, who runs into view singing "I'm Late! I'm Late!," 
Alice falls down the rabbit hole into the topsy-turvy alternate world of 
Wonderland. She grows and shrinks after following the instructions of a 
haughty caterpillar, attends a "Very Merry Unbirthday" party in the garden 
of the Mad Hatter and the March Hare, stands in awe as the Cheshire Cat 
spouts philosophy, listens in rapt attention as Tweedledum and Tweedledee 
relate the story of the Walrus and the Carpenter (a sequence usually cut 
when Alice is shown on TV), and closes out her day with a hectic croquet 
game at the home of the Red Queen. The music and production design of Alice 
in Wonderland is marvellous, but the film is too much of a good thing, much 
too frantic to do full honour to the whimsical Carroll original, and far too 
episodic to hang together as a unified feature film. One tactical error is 
having Alice weep at mid-point, declaring her wish to go home: This is Alice 
in Wonderland, Walt, not Wizard of Oz! Its storytelling shortcomings aside, 
Alice in Wonderland is superior family entertainment (never mind the efforts 
in the 1970s to palm off the picture as a psychedelic "head" film).
